Best, worst, and average case.

The same algorithm can behave very differently depending on the input it receives. The best case is the most favourable input possible — the one that lets the algorithm finish as quickly as it ever can. The worst case is the most demanding input — the one that forces the algorithm to do the maximum amount of work. The average case is the expected performance across typical inputs.

In practice, worst case is what matters most. It is the guarantee you can give. When someone asks what the complexity of your algorithm is, they almost always mean worst case.

Linear search is a clear illustration. The best case is constant time — the target happens to be the very first element. The worst case is linear time — the target is last, or not in the list at all. The average case is also linear time, because on average you check half the elements, and half of n is still proportional to n.
